ence level. The identification of five case relations and of verbs that are impersonal provides explanations for seeming problems of grammatical agreement.The grammar avoids technical terminology, especially in the early chapters, and is aimed at educated laypersons—teachers and college students—who either speak the language or are motivated to learn it. It is rich with examples for each topic, including words exemplifying the contrasts in the sound system and sentences that highlight special points and intricacies in constructions such as cleft sentences and the phenomenon known as switch reference.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 25. Feb 2021) 7aFOREIGN LANGUAGE STUDY / Oceanic & Australian Languages.2bisacsh1 aBlust, Robert A., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCapelle, Alfred, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aPagotto, Louise, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHawaii eBook Package 2014-2016z978311056413608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPP Plus eBook-Package 2016z978311070101240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978082485996140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780824859961423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780824859961.jpg  a978-3-11-056413-6  Hawaii eBook Package 2014-2016c2014d2016  a978-3-11-070101-2  PP Plus eBook-Package 2016b2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles